out and allowed the elements to break out into the margins.","source":"Coralie Bickford-Smith/Penguin","credit":"Illustration: Coralie Bickford-Smith/Penguin","mediaId":"32d6558f696bdc23305db73347c29ef891e6c55f","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Illustration","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/32d6558f696bdc23305db73347c29ef891e6c55f/0_0_4182_2953/2000.jpg","width":"2000","height":"1412"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/32d6558f696bdc23305db73347c29ef891e6c55f/0_0_4182_2953/1000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/32d6558f696bdc23305db73347c29ef891e6c55f","altText":"Fox and Star 1","caption":"Although <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/316571/s/the-fox-and-the-star/\">The Fox and the Star</a> looks like a children’s book I wanted the story to be something that resonated with adults as well. The page layout and design were heavily influenced by William Blake and William Morris, evoking a sense of illuminated manuscripts and traditional fairytales. Where I felt it appropriate I playfully dispensed with the strict layout and allowed the elements to break out into the margins.","source":"Coralie Bickford-Smith/Penguin","credit":"Illustration: Coralie Bickford-Smith/Penguin","mediaId":"32d6558f696bdc23305db73347c29ef891e6c55f","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Illustration","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/32d6558f696bdc23305db73347c29ef891e6c55f/0_0_4182_2953/1000.jpg","width":"1000","height":"706"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/32d6558f696bdc23305db73347c29ef891e6c55f/0_0_4182_2953/500.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/32d6558f696bdc23305db73347c29ef891e6c55f","altText":"Fox and Star 1","caption":"Although <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/316571/s/the-fox-and-the-star/\">The Fox and the Star</a> looks like a children’s book I wanted the 