guardian.com/theguardian/g2","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/g2","sectionName":"From the Guardian","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/g2/arts","webTitle":"Arts","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/g2/arts","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/g2/arts","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"id":"books/2015/nov/30/the-typewriter-revolution-richard-polt-typosphere","rights":{"syndicatable":"false"},"type":"article","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Typists of the world, unite! A new book looks inside the 'typosphere'","webPublicationDate":"2015-11-30T16:04:18Z","fields":{"wordcount":"804","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4efx9","liveBloggingNow":"false","body":"<p>At the <a href=\"http://miamibookfair.com/\">Miami Book Fair</a> earlier this month, <a href=\"http://site.xavier.edu/polt/typewriters/\">Richard Polt </a>arrived equipped with both a PowerPoint presentation and a Groma Kolibri, his vintage “laptop typewriter” made in East Germany in 1956. The antique machine – incidentally, the same model preferred by the writer Will Self – is stylish and durable, less of a prop than a symbol of an insurgency aided and abetted by Polt, author of <a href=\"http://books.wwnorton.com/books/detail.aspx?id=4294988995\">The Typewriter Revolution: A Typist’s Companion for the 21st Century</a>.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/gallery/2011/may/11/authors-typewriters-in-pictures\">Key workers: writers at their typewriters - in pictures</a> </p> </aside>  <p>You’d never guess that the mild-mannered professor of philosophy at Xavier University in Cincinnati, Ohio, is a radical. Yet, his book opens with a manifesto that asserts the right to “resist the paradigm” and “escape the data stream”.</p> <p>Polt typed that original declaration in 2012, motivated by an irritation with digital life and the knowledge that lots of young people were doing interesting things with typewriters. “The fact is that they’re turning to something non-digital for something that’s usually done digitally,” he pointed out during an interview prior to the book fair. </p> <p>Having collected typewriters for more than 20 years, Polt decided to join the “typosphere” and start “typecasting”. Simply put, he uses a typewriter to capture his thoughts, then scans the page and uploads it to his blog. (He maintains two websites: <a href=\"http://site.xavier.edu/polt/typewriters/\">The Classic Typewriter</a> and <a href=\"http://writingball.blogspot.com/\">The Typewriter Revolution</a>.) </p> <p>He also began attending and hosting type-ins, which he describes in his book as “public acts of typewriting”. These informal events unite like-minded typists for swapping, letter writing, speed contests and, sometimes, political activism. The first type-in was held in Philadelphia in 2010 by a “band of renegades assembled at Bridgewater’s Pub in Philadelphia”. Other, more practical acts of typing nonconformity followed: Occupy Wall Street protestors in Portland, Oregon, conducted type-ins once their power had been cut off by the local authorities.</p> <p>The mania for old-fashioned typewriters has only intensified in recent years. There is now a service called <a href=\"http://typewriterrodeo.com/\">Typewriter Rodeo</a> that provides custom, on-demand, typewritten poetry at social events. Tom Hanks – yes, that one – created a top-selling <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/aug/19/tom-hanks-hanx-writer-typewriter-app-itunes-chart\">typewriter app</a>. At this year’s Burning Man, there was the installation of an enormous, climbable typewriter called the <a href=\"http://burningman.org/event/brc/2015-art-installations/#BlunderwoodPortable\">Blunderwood Portable</a>. And, in addition to Polt’s guide, two other books devoted to typewriters and typewriter art were published this fall: Tony Allan’s illustrated gift book, <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Typewriter-The-History-Machines-Writers/dp/1627950346\">The Typewriter: the History, the Machines, the Writers</a>, for which Polt served as consultant, and Ruth and Marvin Sackner’s <a href=\"http://www.thamesandhudsonusa.com/books/the-art-of-typewriting-hardcover\">The Art of Typewriting</a>. </p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2014/nov/05/tom-hanks-typewriter-stories-great-novels\">Tom Hanks beware: typewriters spawned rubbish as well as great novels</a> </p> </aside>  <p>But those who might hurl terms like “nostalgic” or “hipster” at the 50-year-old Polt and his comrades would be missing the mark. Polt locates the typewriter trend in the “slow movement” and the “maker movement” – both of which play into the idea that denizens of the 21st century need digital detox – but he connects his analog passion to contemporary issues of sustainability. Modern technology requires constant updating and replacement, but the decades-old machines that Polt picks up in thrift shops and on eBay can often be refurbished with elbow grease and simple instructions (which he provides in his book, natch).</p> <p>These so-called defunct machines are also better at keeping secrets, which is why Polt also views the typewriter as an anti-surveillance tool. It was, he said, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/us-news/the-nsa-files\">revelations about the National Security Administration’s spying</a> that ultimately crystallised this project for him. After all, unlike email, typewritten correspondence cannot be hacked. (Government agencies, he reports, are the primary consumers of new typewriters.) </p> <p>The title of one of the chapters in Polt’s book is Choose Your Weapon. It may seem tongue-in-cheek, but the gun manufacturer Remington was actually one of the most popular 20th-century producers of standard and midsize typewriters alongside Royal, Olympia, Smith-Corona, Underwood, Olivetti and Hermes. Polt, whose personal collection of typewriters numbers around 300, was hard-pressed to name a favourite, but he is a fan of the 1937 Remington Noiseless Model Seven, his first typewriter, acquired in the late 1970s.</p> <p>As for his fulminating against digital life, he said: “It’s in the spirit of fun but it’s also sincere. I think these are real problems and we’re all aware of them now – that our digital activities erode our privacy, and they erode our ability to focus and concentrate, and they create a lot of superficial connections to other people but they’re not necessarily good for deep connections.”</p> <p>That said, Polt shuns neither computers nor social media, but he does believe that we need some distance from our devices. “At the most abstract level, that’s the message I’m trying to send with my book – that we need some perspective. We shouldn’t be wrapped up in the present day and present technology, so whether it’s through typewriters or some other device or just stepping away from your computer or role-playing or whatever it is, perspective is healthy.”<br /></p>","productionOffice":"US","hasStoryPackage":"false","trailText":"Some might call typewriters a dead technology but a quiet revival is afoot, claims philosophy professor Richard Polt – spurred, in his case, by a fear of surveillance","headline":"Typists of the world, unite! A new book looks inside the 'typosphere'","byline":"Rebecca Rego Barry","commentable":"true","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/8b6ed6974e237aab30646748b35f2200cc9b3a1d/0_426_5017_3009/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2015-12-03T16:04:18Z","standfirst":"<p>Some might call typewriters a dead technology but a quiet revival is afoot, claims philosophy professor Richard Polt – spurred, in his case, by a fear of surveillance</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/30/the-typewriter-revolution-richard-polt-ty